---
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";

const baseUrl = import.meta.env.BASE_URL.endsWith("/")
  ? import.meta.env.BASE_URL
  : `${import.meta.env.BASE_URL}/`;
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Artist Share vs Label Share | How Much Music"
  description="Why gross music revenue and artist-side take-home are different numbers."
  type="article"
>
  <section>
    <p class="eyebrow">Explainer</p>
    <h1>Artist share vs label share</h1>
    <p>
      A song can generate a large gross revenue number while the artist keeps only part of it.
      Gross track or catalog revenue should be separated from artist-side income because labels,
      distributors, publishers, songwriters, managers, and recoupment terms can all sit between the
      listener and the performer.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>The simple version</h2>
    <ul class="meta-list">
      <li><strong>Gross revenue</strong> is the broader money pool attached to the recording, composition, or catalog.</li>
      <li><strong>Label share</strong> usually sits on the master-recording side and can be meaningful for major-label releases.</li>
      <li><strong>Artist share</strong> is the modeled take-home lane after relevant rights-holder splits and assumptions.</li>
      <li><strong>Publishing share</strong> is separate from the master and may flow to songwriters, publishers, or catalog buyers.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Why the difference matters</h2>
    <p>
      Two songs can look similar on streaming charts but behave differently as income assets. A
      self-controlled catalog, a favorable royalty contract, or retained publishing can make a
      smaller gross number more valuable to the artist than a larger recording with heavy label or
      publishing claims.
    </p>
    <p>
      This is why split-aware estimates matter: they make clear when the artist-side and label-side
      ranges can be separated.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>A practical reading order</h2>
    <ul class="meta-list">
      <li>Start with the artist-side estimate if the question is "what might the artist or estate keep?"</li>
      <li>Use gross revenue to understand the total economic size of the song or catalog.</li>
      <li>Use label and publishing lanes to understand why the gross number does not flow to one person.</li>
      <li>Check methodology notes before comparing two pages, because confidence levels and available source context can differ.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>How to read the estimates</h2>
    <ul class="meta-list">
      <li>Use gross revenue as a scale signal, not as the artist's personal income.</li>
      <li>Use artist-side estimates when comparing how valuable a catalog may be to the performer or estate.</li>
      <li>Use label-side estimates to understand why recorded-music rights can remain valuable to companies and catalog buyers.</li>
      <li>Check ownership notes because sales, publishing splits, and estate control can materially change the final picture.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      For the broader model, read the <a href={`${baseUrl}insights/methodology/`}>full methodology</a>
      and the <a href={`${baseUrl}insights/catalog-ownership/`}>catalog ownership explainer</a>.
    </p>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
